<feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><title>ഇന്നത്തെ ചിന്താവിഷയം | Thoughts of the Day</title><subtitle>A web-log / common place notebook</subtitle><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/atom.xml" rel="self"></link><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net"></link><author><name>undefined</name></author><id>770be307-4a92-7999-f61e-e980a2456c90</id><updated>2024-12-24T16:34:49</updated><entry><title>2024-12-23</title><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/#2024-12-23"></link><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/static/2024-12-23.html" rel="alternative" type="text/html"></link><id>a10567df-7eeb-dcaf-237d-d69613d6cee9</id><updated>2024-12-24T00:09:54</updated><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><ul><li><a class="tc-tiddlylink-external" href="https://pluralistic.net/2021/05/09/the-memex-method/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">https://pluralistic.net/2021/05/09/the-memex-method/</a><ul><li>Revisited the whole reason I decided to resurrect this blog. </li><li>Feels right to do this before the new year starts rather than during or with the new year. I feel like its takes the pressure out from the day.</li></ul></li></ul><br></br><ul><li><a class="tc-tiddlylink-external" href="https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/JBR6AF9Gusv4u6Fwo/laziness-death-spirals?utm_source=pocket_shared" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">https://www.lesswrong.com/posts/JBR6AF9Gusv4u6Fwo/laziness-death-spirals?utm_source=pocket_shared</a><ul><li>A first person account of laziness and procrastination that really resonated with me. </li><li>I realized that I had also stumbled upon some of the strategies listed in this essay in my lifelong battle with procrastination and poor attention/focus.</li></ul></li></ul></div></content><author><name>undefined</name></author></entry><entry><title>2024-12-24</title><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/#2024-12-24"></link><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/static/2024-12-24.html" rel="alternative" type="text/html"></link><id>aa18e6e1-7615-8eec-bd81-5f7c8e7a41b9</id><updated>2024-12-24T16:34:49</updated><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><ul><li><a class="tc-tiddlylink-external" href="https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2024/12/trust-issues-in-ai.html" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">https://www.schneier.com/blog/archives/2024/12/trust-issues-in-ai.html</a></li><li><a class="tc-tiddlylink-external" href="https://ludic.mataroa.blog/blog/you-must-read-at-least-one-book-to-ride/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">https://ludic.mataroa.blog/blog/you-must-read-at-least-one-book-to-ride/</a></li></ul></div></content><author><name>undefined</name></author></entry><entry><title>Hello World</title><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/#Hello%20World"></link><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/static/Hello%2520World.html" rel="alternative" type="text/html"></link><id>b10a8db1-64e0-7541-05b7-a99be72e3fe5</id><updated>2024-12-24T11:24:14</updated><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><p>This &quot;notebook&quot; is an attempt at complying to the spirit of &quot;working with the garage door open&quot;.</p><p>Over the past year or two, I came across two concepts or essays that have left a lasting impression on me, specifically around how I go about thinking, reading and learning.</p><ol><li>Cory Doctorow's <a class="tc-tiddlylink-external" href="https://pluralistic.net/2021/05/09/the-memex-method/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">treatise</a> on how he combined the traditional <a class="tc-tiddlylink-external" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commonplace_book" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">common place book</a>  and a web-log(or blog) with a daily writing practice </li><li>Piotr Wozniak and his concept of <a class="tc-tiddlylink-external" href="https://supermemo.guru/wiki/Incremental_reading" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">''Incremental Reading''</a></li></ol><h2 class="">Whats in the box?</h2><p>Broadly speaking this notebook contains (or is expected to contain) 3 different types of writing</p><ol><li>Daily web logs of links I find interesting and/or random musings</li><li>Book notes - In the spirit of incremental reading, these are usually in flashcard/cloze format and I use a tiddlywiki plugin that syncs them to Anki (the most popular free software spaced repetition solution)</li><li>Essays and Long form writing that I hope to produce sporadically</li></ol></div></content><author><name>undefined</name></author></entry><entry><title>Letters from a Stoic</title><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/#Letters%20from%20a%20Stoic"></link><link href="blog.waitsforsleep.net/static/Letters%2520from%2520a%2520Stoic.html" rel="alternative" type="text/html"></link><id>1ff7fd57-1f1a-64f2-a8ae-ec8381cefa11</id><updated>2024-12-24T09:58:35</updated><content type="xhtml"><div xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml"><h2 class="">Letter 2</h2><h2 class="">Letter 3</h2><h2 class="">Letter 5</h2><h2 class="">Letter 7</h2><h2 class="">Letter 9</h2><h2 class="">Letter 12</h2></div></content><author><name>undefined</name></author></entry></feed>

